    <text>
        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC">              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="stroke"/><unclear reason="ambiguous">ᚁ</unclear>ᚊᚔ<g ref="#punctuation_double"/> ᚐ<unclear reason="ambiguous">ᚁ</unclear><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="stroke"/>
                </ab> 
            </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="stroke"/><unclear reason="ambiguous">B</unclear>QI<g ref="#punctuation_double"/> A<unclear reason="ambiguous">B</unclear><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="stroke"/>
                </ab>
                <ab type="list">[---]BQI: AB[---]</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app n="1">
                        <note>The direction of the reading is determined by the forward slope of the second letter in the extant text.</note>
                    </app>
                <app n="2">
                    <note>The inscription may preserve evidence of the double dot which marks word division and aids the segmentation of the text.</note>                    
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>The text is incomplete and it is not possible to determine its meaning.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                 <p>The scale of the letters and the extant reading imply that this is only a short section of a larger text. However, there is no clue to determine where in the sequence this portion occurred (Forsyth 1996, 82). </p>
                <p>It is possible that the letters AQI could be Old Irish MAQI. If so, this would be the only Scottish example of the word spelled with a single Q (Forsyth 1996, 85).</p>
            </div>
